T1  - Bank Monitoring with On-Site Inspections
AU  - Heitz, Amanda Rae
AU  - Martin, Christopher
AU  - Ufier, Alexander
Y1  - 2026/04/01
PY  - 2026
DA  - 2026/04/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.70026
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - J Finance
SP  - 687
EP  - 737
VL  - 81
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.70026
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - ABSTRACT Using proprietary transaction-level data on nonsyndicated construction loans, we provide some of the first empirical evidence on the drivers and consequences of bank monitoring through on-site inspections.  Banks trade off monitoring intensity with favorable origination terms. Monitoring intensity escalates in response to local economic downturns or the bank's financial instability.  Borrowers with negative inspection reports have more draw requests denied, suggesting that monitoring outcomes impact credit decisions. Both the occurrence and threat of increased inspection frequency correspond to reduced defaults. Overall, our results provide empirical support for a substantial body of theoretical literature on bank monitoring.
ER  - 

