T1  - Investor Composition and the Liquidity Component in the U.S. Corporate Bond Market
AU  - LI, JIAN
AU  - YU, HAIYUE
Y1  - 2026/04/01
PY  - 2026
DA  - 2026/04/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.70024
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - J Finance
SP  - 871
EP  - 922
VL  - 81
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.70024
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - ABSTRACT The link between corporate bond credit spreads and secondary market illiquidity in the cross section has grown stronger since 2005, resulting in a higher liquidity component in credit spreads. Using U.S. investor holdings data, we show that short-term investors (e.g., mutual funds/exchange-traded funds [ETFs]) increase trading activities in the secondary market, amplifying the effect of secondary market frictions on prices. We provide a model featuring heterogeneous investors with different trading needs and heterogeneous bonds to investigate the impact of the rapid-growing mutual fund/ETF sector on the corporate bond market. We find the change in investor composition can quantitatively explain the aggregate trend.
ER  - 
